### Laravel Version

11.42.0

### PHP Version

8.3.15

### Database Driver & Version

_No response_

### Description

The ``UseFactory`` attribute [introduced in v11.39.0](https://github.com/laravel/framework/commit/ffa1a12b7ff81690a35487ac583eb8ec0c2660f5) causes problems when you create a model with the ``UseFactory`` attribute and then a model that doesn't specify it. The ``HasFactory`` trait calls ``guessModelNamesUsing`` in the ``Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Factories\Factory``, which sets a static property that then applies to all classes that inherit ``Factory``. 

The bug ultimately originates from the model name resolver being set in the [Factory class](https://github.com/laravel/framework/blob/17786ca25fa9080f0b4f03af7517e9fc72fa0b4a/src/Illuminate/Database/Eloquent/Factories/Factory.php#L838). It's setting the ``$modelNameResolver`` property for ``Factory`` and every class that inherits ``Factory``. 

## Possible Solutions

1. Change the ``$modelNameResolver`` property in ``src\Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Factories\Factory.php`` to an array, which holds a implemented factory class name with a resolver:

```php
protected static $modelNameResolver = [];

// ...

public function modelName()
{
  // ...
  $resolver = static::$modelNameResolver[static::class] ?? function (self $factory) {
    // ...
  };
  // ...
}

// ...

public static function guessModelNamesUsing(callable $callback)
{
  static::$modelNameResolver[static::class] = $callback;
}
```

2. Require the ``UseFactory`` attribute set for all or none of the models. This would mean updating the documentation.


### Steps To Reproduce

The repository is located at: https://github.com/SameOldNick/laravel-factory-bug

#### Install Steps

1. Clone the repo: ``git clone https://github.com/SameOldNick/laravel-factory-bug``
2. Install Composer packages: ``composer install``
3. Create .env file: ``cp .env.example .env``
4. Run PHPUnit test case: ``php artisan test --filter=BugTest``

#### Copy of Problem Code

For the record, I've included the problem code. The ``Role`` class has the ``UseFactory`` attribute set, while the ``User`` class doesn't.

```php
// Works fine
Role::factory(5)->create();

// Will try insert into roles table
User::factory()->create([
  'name' => 'Test User',
  'email' => 'test@example.com',
]);
```
